signature_matches.description: communication : all known techniques for sending data to a potential C2 server
signature_matches.rule_src:
rule:
  meta:
    name: send data
    namespace: communication
    authors:
      - william.ballenthin@mandiant.com
      - joakim@intezer.com
    description: all known techniques for sending data to a potential C2 server
    scope: function
    mbc:
      - Command and Control::C2 Communication::Send Data [B0030.001]
    examples:
      - BFB9B5391A13D0AFD787E87AB90F14F5:0x13145D60
  features:
    - or:
      - and:
        - os: windows
        - or:
          - match: send HTTP request
          - match: send data on socket
          - match: send file via HTTP
          - match: send data to Internet
      - and:
        - os: linux
        - or: # Require network bound socket.
          - match: create TCP socket
          - match: create UDP socket
        - or:
          - match: send HTTP request
          - match: send data on socket
          - match: send file via HTTP

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects execution of Net.exe, whether suspicious or benign.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Michael Haag, Mark Woan (improvements), James Pemberton / @4A616D6573 / oscd.community (improvements)

T1091.description: Checks for available system drives (often done to infect USB drives)

T1059.description: Uses cmd line tools excessively to alter registry or file data
Very long cmdline option found, this is very uncommon (may be encrypted or packed)

T1569.002.description: Uses sc.exe to modify the status of services

T1543.003.description: Uses sc.exe to modify the status of services

T1547.001.description: Stores files to the Windows startup directory

T1574.010.description: Uses cacls to modify the permissions of files

T1055.description: Injects a PE file into a foreign processes

T1562.001.description: Creates guard pages, often used to prevent reverse engineering and debugging

T1070.004.description: May delete shadow drive data (may be related to ransomware)

T1036.description: Creates files inside the user directory

T1112.description: Uses reg.exe to modify the Windows registry

T1497.description: May sleep (evasive loops) to hinder dynamic analysis

T1564.001.description: Creates files in the recycle bin to hide itself

T1120.description: Checks for available system drives (often done to infect USB drives)
Sample is looking for USB drives. Launch the sample with the USB Fake Disk cookbook

T1083.description: Searches for user specific document files

T1082.description: Checks the free space of harddrives
Queries the volume information (name, serial number etc) of a device

T1518.001.description: May try to detect the virtual machine to hinder analysis (VM artifact strings found in memory)
Tries to detect sandboxes and other dynamic analysis tools

T1057.description: Queries a list of all running processes

T1010.description: Sample monitors Window changes (e.g. starting applications), analyze the sample with the simulation cookbook

T1016.description: Checks the online ip address of the machine

T1005.description: Searches for user specific document files

T1105.description: Downloads files from webservers via HTTP
Some HTTP requests failed (404). It is likely the sample will exhibit less behavior
Tries to download or post to a non-existing http route (HTTP/1.1 404 Not Found / 503 Service Unavailable)

T1573.description: Uses HTTPS for network communication, use the SSL MITM Proxy cookbook for further analysis

T1095.description: Downloads files from webservers via HTTP
Tries to download or post to a non-existing http route (HTTP/1.1 404 Not Found / 503 Service Unavailable)

T1071.description: Downloads files from webservers via HTTP
Tries to download or post to a non-existing http route (HTTP/1.1 404 Not Found / 503 Service Unavailable)

T1486.description: Writes a notice file (html or txt) to demand a ransom

T1490.description: Uses bcdedit to modify the Windows boot settings
